<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=902335902&t=artid%3d30572f02-446c-4beb-93dd-41c21b8f66e7%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/Sport/Article&sz=300x250&c=902335902&t=artid%3d30572f02-446c-4beb-93dd-41c21b8f66e7%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>The teams went into the match having collected six points each and were level on goal difference, but Amajita proved too strong for the Egyptians.Amajita will face the Group A runners-up in the semifinals at Arthur Davies Stadium in Kitwe on Thursday. Thabo Senong’s charges lost in the final of the tournament last year, suffering a 2-1 defeat to this year’s hosts Zambia at Moruleng Stadium in Rustenburg.Senong was impressed with the lads’ performance, saying: “Good character from our boys, well done to them. We beat a good team. “It’s all about development and our boys need to develop mentally. We are happy with the win and look forward to the semifinals. We are prepared to face any side.”He added: “We are here to learn, to keep our regeneration fresh. It’s always important to play against tough opponents. We are flexible in selection and will put up a strong team for the semis.”Amajita midfielder Lehlogonolo Matlou, who won the Man of the Match award yesterday, said: “I am happy and honoured to play in this tournament. This award will motivate me going forward. I won’t stop working hard. “We won through hard work today. Our focus was not on our opponents but on the game and in the end we got the result.”
